>It's been revealed that there are some glaring holes in a Youtube video claiming audio evidence of Russian separatists discussing the takedown of Malaysia Airlines MH17. The flight crash killed 298 innocent people in a Russian breakaway region of Ukrainian territory.

>The supposedly captured audio of two Russian separatists discussing the crash was widely posted in the media. But when it comes to information warfare regarding Russia and the Ukraine, it's wise to be highly cautious before spreading such disinformation. This case shows one reason why.

>...The one major problem is that many claim the timestamps of the video's “creation time” put it at July 16, one day prior to the Malaysia Airlines crash on July 17. Then it was published by “Anonymous” on July 18. This screenshot comes via Zerohedge

>...In addition to the timestamp issue, there is the problem of logic. Why and how would unencrypted military communications be captured and cleared for public dissemination through a Youtube channel so quickly?

>Wouldn't it have been more effective for the Ukrainian government to verify the transmission as authentic, and host a press conference inviting CNN, the BBC, and other major world outlets to report on it?

>A videoblogger DahBoo77 dissected the timestamp and purportedly found the video was uploaded 810 times - prior to the plane being shot down. Other questions have arisen, one posed on Zerohedge, about similarly formatted videos, such as one uploaded by “Ukraine Investigation” blaming “Cossacks” for chaos in Russia.

